        "number": 2,
        "title": "The daughter's vow — paternal authority as covenantal stewardship",
        "range": "30:3-5",
        "excerpt": "And her father hears her vow and her obligation by which she has bound herself, and her father says nothing to her, then all her vows shall stand.",
        "body": "The chapter's first case involves a young unmarried woman (*naur*, a girl still in her youth) living in her father's house. She makes a vow to the LORD. The text immediately introduces the father: 'her father hears.' The legal outcome depends entirely on what the father does with what he has heard. Silence confirms (v.4); timely prohibition voids the vow and the LORD forgives the daughter (v.5).\n\nThe structure of the law reflects Israel's household theology. The *bet av* (father's house) was the basic unit of Israel's tribal and covenantal life. The father was not only the biological progenitor but the covenant head of the household — the one responsible for its life before Yahweh (cf. Joshua 24:15, 'as for me and my house, we will serve the LORD'). A daughter's vow, made while she is under that covenantal covering, falls within the sphere of paternal responsibility. The father is not given authority to arbitrarily override his daughter's spirituality; he is given a one-day window to exercise stewardship over a commitment made under his roof.\n\nThe provision of divine forgiveness (v.5, *salach*) is the chapter's first pastoral grace note. The LORD does not penalize the daughter for a commitment she made sincerely but that her father had legitimate authority to redirect. The guilt for the unfulfilled vow does not cling to her. This is not a second-class treatment of the daughter's spiritual seriousness — it is the gracious provision of a God who holds the authority figure accountable and releases the person under authority from guilt when the system functions correctly.\n\nThe Reformed tradition has often read this structure through Ephesians 5-6 and 1 Corinthians 7 — households structured by differentiated authority and shared accountability before God. Calvin's comment on this passage (*Harmony of the Pentateuch*) notes that the law 'does not dishonor the vow of a daughter or wife, but honors the order God has appointed in households.' The authority is always instrumentalized toward the household's flourishing before God, never toward the suppression of the subordinate party's covenant life.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Charash* (silence) — five occurrences in the chapter, always as the legally active mechanism of confirmation. The word can also mean 'to plow' (making a furrow, engraving) — silence here cuts a legal groove, it is not the absence of action."
